            <h2>The ghost and the boy</h2>
          
            <p class="summary">
              Timmy was scared of everything. He didn't like trying new things. He was too nervous to speak up in class, join games, or even ride his bike without training wheels. “What if I fall? What if I mess up?” Timmy always asked. 
            </p>
            <p class="full-content" style="display: none;">
              One day, Timmy's family moved to a new house on Bravery Hill. The house was old, creaky, and surrounded by tall, whispering trees. It was the kind of place that made Timmy even more nervous.

              On his first night there, Timmy lay in bed, listening to the wind howl. Suddenly, he heard a soft voice.
              
              “Why so glum, young one?” the voice said.
              
              Timmy shot up, his heart pounding. In the corner of his room stood a glowing figure. It was a ghost! But the ghost wasn't scary at all. She was small, glowing faintly blue, with kind eyes and a warm smile.
              
              “Who are you?” Timmy whispered.
              
              “I'm Clara,” the ghost said. “I used to live here many, many years ago. I help kids who are scared. And you, my boy, seem to be scared of a lot.”
              
              Timmy's face turned red. “I just… don't think I'm good at anything,” he said. “I'm always too scared to try.”
              
              Clara smiled gently. “Let's change that. Tomorrow, we'll start small.”
              <br></br>
              The next morning, Clara was waiting by the door when Timmy woke up. “What's the first thing you're afraid of?” she asked.

              Timmy thought for a moment. “Riding my bike without training wheels,” he admitted.

                “Perfect,” Clara said. She floated outside, glowing in the morning sun.

                Timmy wobbled onto his bike as Clara floated beside him. “If you fall, I'll catch you," she said.

              Timmy took a deep breath. He pushed off, his legs shaking. At first, the bike wobbled. Then it steadied. Timmy was riding!

              “Look at me!” he yelled, a big grin on his face.

              “You did it all on your own,” Clara said, beaming. “Now, what's next?”
              <br></br>

              Over the next few days, Clara helped Timmy face more fears. She stood by his side when he raised his hand in class, whispering, “You’ve got this.” She cheered quietly when he joined a soccer game during recess.

                 One evening, Clara asked, “What's the one thing you're most scared of?”

                Timmy frowned. “Talking to people I don't know,” he said.

                Clara nodded. “Tomorrow, let's try. Just say hello to someone new. That's it.”

                The next day, Timmy saw a boy playing alone at lunch. His stomach churned, but he remembered Clara's words.

                 “Hi, I'm Timmy,” he said.

                The boy smiled. “I'm Jake. Want to play?”

                Timmy's heart soared.
                <br></br>
                That night, Clara appeared one last time.

                 “Timmy,” she said, “you don't need me anymore. You've found your bravery.”

                Timmy felt a lump in his throat. “Thank you, Clara,” he whispered.

                She smiled. “You've always had it in you. Goodbye, my brave friend.”

                   And with that, Clara faded away, leaving Timmy with a new sense of confidence—and a heart full of courage.</p>

